<http://datadock.io/kal/local_data_1/id/resource/monument_record_no/1224M> <http://datadock.io/kal/local_data_1/id/definition/monument_desc> "A brickyard on the south bank of the River Avon, west of Wapping. The yard had a large clay pit at both the west and east ends and operated in the late eighteenth and early nineteenth century. Vitrified bricks from the site were recovered from the river bed in 1998, indicating that waste from the kilns was dumped directly into the river. The clay pits had been filled in by the 1820s. Brunel chose the western clay pit as the site of the Great Western Dry Dock where the SS. Great Britain.\r\nNo structures from the brickyard are known to survive above ground but subsurface survival of features is likely."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> <http://datadock.io/kal/local_data_1/id/dataset/Bristol_Monuments.csv>.
